Akemenidheritageconsulting.com – AKEMENID is a company set up by Alyson Wharton-Durgaryan. It was a trading name used by art and antiquities dealer Hagop Kevorkian in the 1910s for his London shop, as shown by this letterhead. Kevorkian was an Armenian from the Ottoman Empire, but had strong familial and cultural ties to Iran. Akemenid is an idiosyncratic spelling of Achaemenid, – the name of the great Persian classical empire responsible for some of the finest antiquities traded by Kevorkian and other Armenians. I reuse the name Akemenid in fondness for Kevorkian in those early years, and as a reminder that heritage is never simple.
